Security and operational compliance audit - 2026-06-25
Scope: namespace elasticsearch; Elasticsearch cluster es-cluster 8.11.1 via service es-http:9200. This was a read-only audit of the live Elasticsearch configuration; no cluster settings were changed.

Findings:
1. Critical - Authentication is disabled. Unauthenticated HTTP requests to http://es-http.elasticsearch.svc:9200/ return cluster metadata. _xpack/usage reports security.available=true and security.enabled=false. The es-config and es-extra-config ConfigMaps explicitly set xpack.security.enabled: false. Result: no Elasticsearch authentication, authorization, user-role enforcement, field-level security, or document-level security is active.
2. Critical - TLS is disabled for both HTTP and transport. The Elasticsearch config sets xpack.security.http.ssl.enabled: false and xpack.security.transport.ssl.enabled: false on original and expansion nodes. Readiness probes use HTTP. Result: API traffic and inter-node transport are plaintext inside the cluster.
3. High - Network isolation is absent. No NetworkPolicy objects exist in the elasticsearch namespace. Services expose Elasticsearch internally: es-http ClusterIP on 9200, es-extra headless on 9200/9300, and es-cluster headless on 9300. Elasticsearch also binds network.host: 0.0.0.0. Result: any pod with namespace or cluster network reachability can attempt to access these ports.
4. High - User and role audit cannot find active RBAC because security is disabled. Security feature code is available but disabled, so Elasticsearch user and role APIs are not enforcing access control. This is a hardening baseline deviation.
5. Medium - Snapshot repository minio-repo exists and uses S3 bucket es-backups with client default. The es-secure-settings Secret is mounted read-only and contains keys named s3.client.default.access_key and s3.client.default.secret_key; credential values were not read. Credentials were not observed in Elasticsearch ConfigMaps or environment variables. However, s3.client.default.protocol is configured as http, so repository traffic to MinIO is plaintext.
6. Medium - Kubernetes pod hardening is minimal. Elasticsearch pod templates have empty pod securityContext and no container securityContext, so runAsNonRoot, readOnlyRootFilesystem, seccompProfile, and capabilities drop are not declared. The repository-s3 plugin is installed at pod startup by an init container rather than being baked into an immutable image.
7. Operational - Cluster persistent and transient settings are empty. Index app-data has 3 primary shards, 1 replica, index.routing.allocation.include._tier_preference=data_content, and index.routing.allocation.require.node_pool=expansion. This deliberately places app-data on expansion nodes, but reduces placement flexibility if that node pool is unavailable.
8. Operational - Current health is green with 5 nodes and 5 data nodes. es-cluster remains 3/3 replicas. es-extra is 2/2 replicas with node.attr.node_pool=expansion; original es-cluster nodes do not have that node_pool attribute. All app-data shards are STARTED on es-extra-0 and es-extra-1.
9. Snapshot status - minio-repo contains successful snapshots, including snapshot-20260625223035 with app-data and 3 of 3 shards successful.

Recommended remediation for the security team to schedule separately: enable Elasticsearch security and authentication, enable HTTP and transport TLS, add least-privilege users and roles, add restrictive NetworkPolicies, enforce pod securityContext/container securityContext settings, consider HTTPS or equivalent protection for MinIO repository traffic, and review the app-data allocation constraint for resilience.
